Flexperiments for Golf⁣
⁣
Here are a few exercises that I’m using to reinforce some movements that I’d like to see in my own golf swing. ⁣
⁣
The focus of these exercises is not so much building “strength” but using the load as a constraint or teaching aid. With that in mind, I’m using just enough resistance to feel what I want to feel. I’m focused on creating enough of a physical memory to call upon during practice. ⁣
⁣
I’m a lefty golfer, but some of the exercises I’m demonstrating as a righty because it’s a better set up for filming. I do each exercise on both sides when training even when the goal is so movement specific. ⁣

Spin to win.⁣
⁣
CR3DIT @unconventional_strength⁣
⁣
“I think there is a distinct imbalance in training protocols on loading rotational hip action. ⁣
⁣
I see a lot of coaches training straight line actions such as flexion, extension, abduction and adduction but not then expecting the hip to work rotationally in a closed chain. ⁣
⁣
Consider the SAID principle for a second. Basically says if you don’t train it, don’t expect to posses it. There seems to be an assumption that if the linear elements are trained then hip rotation will develop as a result. ⁣
⁣
Sadly, this assumption is why incomplete Strength and conditioning programs are prioritizing linear motions and incorporating rotational motions as “accessory” work, limiting a rotational joint’s potential. ⁣
⁣
If you consider the anatomy of the hip and purpose of the glutes, you see why rotation should be the priority in training. Thankful to have modalities such as @whatsthatstrap and @ancoretraining to work on loading the glutes rotationally, allowing me to play with velocity, stance and vectors of force. ⁣
⁣
This should be paramount in any athletes program…heck any humans program. ⁣
⁣

Golf Fitness Workout Using the 3D Strap, Chop Handle and HTTR Handle⁣
⁣
In response to one of the most common questions/messages, here are 8 exercises that are focused on golf-movement ability. ⁣
⁣
If you choose to try all of these, perform them on a day away from traditional weight training. If you plan a day where you tend to do more mobility and lighter exercises, that would be a good day to do these. ⁣
⁣
You can also do a few of these on each workout day through out the week (2-4 each day x 2-3 workout days).⁣
⁣
How much weight to use: Heavy enough to feel the resistance / Light enough to perform the exercises with a controlled, smooth tempo. Like most exercises, going heavier is a form of progress, but movement control is the goal. Work hard to make it look easy. ⁣
⁣
